text:
Great techniques. Simple and effective that doesn‚Äôt require a lot knowledge and are quick to learn. 

I see comments from fellow martial artists on how these don‚Äôt work and should instead take martial arts classes instead. As a martial artist with my own school I would say this couldn‚Äôt be any more wrong. These techniques have a solid foundation and work. 

Does going a martial arts school and putting in a lot of training put you in a better spot than the basic self defense videos? Absolutely.

Should you not learn any self defense until you do? Absolutely not

First of all not everyone has the resources to attend a martial arts school and train. Sometimes there isn‚Äôt a school nearby, it‚Äôs too expensive, they work late hours when the schools are open, or they are under 18 and their parents won‚Äôt take them. I think many forget that women in abusive relationships can‚Äôt just go out and join a martial arts school and train to protect themselves. In my 20‚Äôs I would go with women in abusive relationships as protection to get their stuff out of their houses/apartments and it would get nasty sometimes. Incredibly controlling and aggressive partners. If the partner were to find out she was going to a martial arts school to train it would have been disastrous. 


Learning these techniques are a great way to learn to defend yourself if you can‚Äôt go to a school or until you can get to the point where you are good enough to defend yourself. It‚Äôs definitely better than not learning how to defend yourself at all. Training at a school takes time, it‚Äôs not going to happen overnight or in week or even in a month. You need something until you reach that point. 

It‚Äôs also videos like this that inspire other women get into martial arts and seek out training to protect themselves because they can see that it can be done.


Absolutely go to a martial arts school when/if you can but that doesn‚Äôt mean you shouldn‚Äôt learn what you can now to help you. 

Awesome video!! Keep them coming.

text:
¬†@kennyhawking8713¬† I‚Äôve been training in martial arts for about 40 years. I‚Äôve been teaching about 15 years. I‚Äôve been doing women‚Äôs self defense for about 5 years. Here is my issue with this kind of view.

They‚Äôre is this notion, this idea that from some reason if you know martial arts, if you are a black belt it somehow automatically gives you the ability to hold you own in a street fight. That if you don‚Äôt take martial arts from a school you clearly can‚Äôt defend yourself. This relies on the flawed idea that all martial arts are taught the same and teaches every student how to defend themselves in a street fight. 

Honestly, a lot martial arts are the opposite. A majority of martial arts teaches students how to strike a stationary bag or a submissive opponent. When I used to compute I would watch my competitors do their forms and they were incredibly accurate, powerful and precise. However, once they got into the ring they had no idea what to do. Cause they never trained with an actual moving target and one that struck back at the same time. I have been contracted by schools to teach their black belts how to better fight because they had no idea how to apply what they learned in actual sparring. 

I wish I had a dollar for every time I had a black belt would try a technique verbatim from a form and end up getting dropped. Your end sentence about ‚Äúif you are attacked just turn 180‚Ä¶‚Äù can literally be replaced with any technique martial arts students learn from a form, or worse yet in a training drill that which has the partner let the counter to an attack just happen.

Usually I find comment like yours based on the ides that they think this is to replace full on martial arts training. it‚Äôs not. It‚Äôs to give them something to use. Some skill is always better than no skill. 

I have had student that watch these videos think they are superstars and know what they are doing. I‚Äôve also had black belts train with me who have next no actual training in sparring think they are amazing cause they only sparred against a stationary bag or an ‚Äúopponent‚Äù that never actually countered them only to find out they have no ability to defend themselves.

I think what a lot of martial arts instructors fail to understand is that a lot of women don‚Äôt have many resources to learn how to protect themselves. I do donation based self defense workshops. In my self defense workshops I‚Äôve had women who have had to hide the fact they were there cause if their abusive partner found out it would be horrible. Women do not always have the resources or luxury of taking martial arts classes. 

To boot having a black belt doesn‚Äôt automatically make you a competent fighter. I‚Äôve gone toe to toe with street fighters with no technical training give me more of a run for my money than most black belts.

I‚Äôve taught the above techniques and they work. I‚Äôve had women reach out to me telling me they helped her. 

I love martial arts and I encourage women to take up classes. However, I will say that if you can‚Äôt take martial arts then this is important to learn. You find a partner and you practice this. Because the quality of martial arts is incredibly subjective. The same mocking tone you take with the video can equally be applied to martial arts itself. 

Again, knowing a little is better than knowing nothing at all. 

Is the above the most ideal way? No

Is learning martial arts the most Ideal way? No

Cause both are only as good as they are taught.

What is ideal is finding someone that can teach you how to fight and the concepts behind it. 

So instead of gatekeeping we should find ways to encourage women who can‚Äôt just easily take ongoing classes to at least find something cause having nothing is worse.

text: The problem is that these techniques rely on a very compliant attacker and don't show what they look like when you meet any measure of actual resistance. I also teach martial arts and I can tell you right now that most of these techniques will not work as advertised and a few of them will actually put you in a more dangerous position than the original attack. The problem with learning self-defense from the internet is 1) you don't have the instructor available to correct bad technique, 2) you likely aren't going to be practicing with proper resistance, 3) most videos don't address what to do if/when things go sideways, and 4) you have to sift through a LOT of bullshido to find effective methods, and most people looking through these videos don't have the background or experience to tell fake martial arts from real martial arts.

So this is what gets me. These are women who are protecting themselves from being attacked, beaten or raped. 

As someone that teaches women‚Äôs self defense the biggest hurdle is to teach them that they can fight back. That they have the power.

These are taught because women are unable to defend themselves. Women who come from abusive relationships who were beaten.

Is your response to them ‚ÄúSo these techniques aren‚Äôt that effective so just keep doing what you were doing when you got beaten up.‚Äù

Women who need these techniques have no way or idea of how to protect themselves. 

At the beginning of my class the women are usually apologizing for hitting or holding back.

Towards the end of the class I have someone in a fully padded suit be non compliant and they fight for their lives. Did they use all the techniques taught to them? No but they did feel like they weren‚Äôt helpless and fought back. And they fought hard.

They tried the take downs and sometimes it worked and sometimes it didn‚Äôt. When it didn‚Äôt they kept going.

Something is better than nothing when your life is on the line

text:
Great techniques. Simple and effective that doesn‚Äôt require a lot knowledge and are quick to learn. 

I see comments from fellow martial artists on how these don‚Äôt work and should instead take martial arts classes instead. As a martial artist with my own school I would say this couldn‚Äôt be any more wrong. These techniques have a solid foundation and work. 

Does going a martial arts school and putting in a lot of training put you in a better spot than the basic self defense videos? Absolutely.

Should you not learn any self defense until you do? Absolutely not

First of all not everyone has the resources to attend a martial arts school and train. Sometimes there isn‚Äôt a school nearby, it‚Äôs too expensive, they work late hours when the schools are open, or they are under 18 and their parents won‚Äôt take them. I think many forget that women in abusive relationships can‚Äôt just go out and join a martial arts school and train to protect themselves. In my 20‚Äôs I would go with women in abusive relationships as protection to get their stuff out of their houses/apartments and it would get nasty sometimes. Incredibly controlling and aggressive partners. If the partner were to find out she was going to a martial arts school to train it would have been disastrous. 


Learning these techniques are a great way to learn to defend yourself if you can‚Äôt go to a school or until you can get to the point where you are good enough to defend yourself. It‚Äôs definitely better than not learning how to defend yourself at all. Training at a school takes time, it‚Äôs not going to happen overnight or in week or even in a month. You need something until you reach that point. 

It‚Äôs also videos like this that inspire other women get into martial arts and seek out training to protect themselves because they can see that it can be done.


Absolutely go to a martial arts school when/if you can but that doesn‚Äôt mean you shouldn‚Äôt learn what you can now to help you. 

Awesome video!! Keep them coming.

text:
¬†@kennyhawking8713¬† I‚Äôve been training in martial arts for about 40 years. I‚Äôve been teaching about 15 years. I‚Äôve been doing women‚Äôs self defense for about 5 years. Here is my issue with this kind of view.

They‚Äôre is this notion, this idea that from some reason if you know martial arts, if you are a black belt it somehow automatically gives you the ability to hold you own in a street fight. That if you don‚Äôt take martial arts from a school you clearly can‚Äôt defend yourself. This relies on the flawed idea that all martial arts are taught the same and teaches every student how to defend themselves in a street fight. 

Honestly, a lot martial arts are the opposite. A majority of martial arts teaches students how to strike a stationary bag or a submissive opponent. When I used to compute I would watch my competitors do their forms and they were incredibly accurate, powerful and precise. However, once they got into the ring they had no idea what to do. Cause they never trained with an actual moving target and one that struck back at the same time. I have been contracted by schools to teach their black belts how to better fight because they had no idea how to apply what they learned in actual sparring. 

I wish I had a dollar for every time I had a black belt would try a technique verbatim from a form and end up getting dropped. Your end sentence about ‚Äúif you are attacked just turn 180‚Ä¶‚Äù can literally be replaced with any technique martial arts students learn from a form, or worse yet in a training drill that which has the partner let the counter to an attack just happen.

Usually I find comment like yours based on the ides that they think this is to replace full on martial arts training. it‚Äôs not. It‚Äôs to give them something to use. Some skill is always better than no skill. 

I have had student that watch these videos think they are superstars and know what they are doing. I‚Äôve also had black belts train with me who have next no actual training in sparring think they are amazing cause they only sparred against a stationary bag or an ‚Äúopponent‚Äù that never actually countered them only to find out they have no ability to defend themselves.

I think what a lot of martial arts instructors fail to understand is that a lot of women don‚Äôt have many resources to learn how to protect themselves. I do donation based self defense workshops. In my self defense workshops I‚Äôve had women who have had to hide the fact they were there cause if their abusive partner found out it would be horrible. Women do not always have the resources or luxury of taking martial arts classes. 

To boot having a black belt doesn‚Äôt automatically make you a competent fighter. I‚Äôve gone toe to toe with street fighters with no technical training give me more of a run for my money than most black belts.

I‚Äôve taught the above techniques and they work. I‚Äôve had women reach out to me telling me they helped her. 

I love martial arts and I encourage women to take up classes. However, I will say that if you can‚Äôt take martial arts then this is important to learn. You find a partner and you practice this. Because the quality of martial arts is incredibly subjective. The same mocking tone you take with the video can equally be applied to martial arts itself. 

Again, knowing a little is better than knowing nothing at all. 

Is the above the most ideal way? No

Is learning martial arts the most Ideal way? No

Cause both are only as good as they are taught.

What is ideal is finding someone that can teach you how to fight and the concepts behind it. 

So instead of gatekeeping we should find ways to encourage women who can‚Äôt just easily take ongoing classes to at least find something cause having nothing is worse.

text: The problem is that these techniques rely on a very compliant attacker and don't show what they look like when you meet any measure of actual resistance. I also teach martial arts and I can tell you right now that most of these techniques will not work as advertised and a few of them will actually put you in a more dangerous position than the original attack. The problem with learning self-defense from the internet is 1) you don't have the instructor available to correct bad technique, 2) you likely aren't going to be practicing with proper resistance, 3) most videos don't address what to do if/when things go sideways, and 4) you have to sift through a LOT of bullshido to find effective methods, and most people looking through these videos don't have the background or experience to tell fake martial arts from real martial arts.

text: I hope at some point, in one of your videos, you cover confidence. I teach a women's self defence class, I'm also female, nearly Every woman I have taught, lacks the confidence to protect themselves, for fear of being hurt or getting into trouble. it can take weeks or months to get a student to the point where they feel that they could use what they have learned. there are also more effective defences against a double hand throat grab, but everything else on this video was spot on, though sometimes it is not possible to run. I had a student join my class after the had been assaulted during a taxi ride. I tell all my students, never sit next to the driver, always sit directly behind them, and never get them to drop you off right at your door, by sitting directly behind the driver, if they divert from the place you know you have access to them, but they cannot reach you.....if you are in the back seat and they intend to kidnap you, go for the eyes, use you bag strap to strangle them or a coat or even your arms. once thatbperaon takes you from point A to point B your chances of survival drop. don't walk down the street with head phones in, so many women have been attacked simply because they did not pay attention to their surroundings. and you cannot learn what you need to know from a 10 min video....it takes practice, and confidence and knowing that it is perfectly ok to defend yourself

text:
My daughter asks about the front choke escape. 
What if you don't  break the hold. I suggested to twist the opposite direction into a hard back hand to the nose or an elbow as she may already have pulled him off balance. I will have to practice this with her. What do you do when you can't totally break the hold?  I liked the hair grab defense. Personally I wouldn't have thought of it. I thought a parting kick as you start to step off into your run striking him with a lifting heel kick into his gut or groin however it lands to further slow him down. The rear grab...
He looks like you hit him in the groin after you have executed the technique, but there is no strike to show how this happens is there a hard bump with your hip to bend him like that? What if you are physically not able to break the hold even when you try the technique perfectly? Is there a strike with the back of your head into his nose and mouth and then in his more softened up state, then execute the technique. Add a palm strike to the groin and run. If you're in danger, cause the most damage to slow down or stop the attacker. I say that because of all my female friends and I being a 54 year old man, I can still outrun most of them. If you make the guy mad, then the two step technique is not enough to get away. He will simply run you down and be more wise to you and more careful about how he responds to your technique if he is totally a bad person and out to harm you anyway. Most men who you may encounter are fairly decent guys and you can simply say stop or don't and they will respect you with out violence. If they don't, and you have to enforce the respect and do the technique, then they may act hurt but they will (or  should) still respect your reaction and decision not to be touched or messed with and give you your space. Otherwise smash him hard and get to a large crowd of people who can help you. There's always one or more people who will stand up and fight for your decision to be left alone. The rest of these seem solid. Those are my issues as a father and grandfather. They don't seem to be complete techniques without the finishing strikes that make sure the guy doesn't keep following you and keep attacking you. Disable him, stun him, cause him pain to the point that you slow him down, and then you run. Then he is less likely to come after you after you execute your technique and begin to make your escape.
